1 Introduction

This document is to make a heatmap for the paper âPlasma proteomic biomarkers as mediators or moderators for the association between poor cardiovascular health and white matter microstructural integrity: The UK Biobank studyâ (Paper13) by May Ahmad Baydoun, et al. The data is from the email from May Ahmad on Feb 13, 2024.

Email from Baydoun, May Ahmad on Feb 13, 2024.

Instructions in Mayâs email

In the meantime, I need your help putting together a heatmap that is very similar to paper #7 (NODDI paper, published in BBI this year).

I am attaching the code that you sent me for that paper along with the excel sheet for the results for this one.

Basically, this one has FA, MD, ISOVF, ICVF, and OD with the same type of ROIs plus means. It is expected that the predictor is negatively associated with FA and ICVF and positively associated with MD, ISOVF and OD. The predictor reflect poor cardiovascular health using LE8 measure.

This will be basically be Figure 1 for this paper, which shows the results of the regression models for poor CVH Ã  dMRI outcomes, adjusting for confounders. LE8 is z-scored and dMRI measures are also z-scored. So, we would expect the effect estimate to be somewhere between -1 and +1, but most of the effect sizes are between -0.13 and +0.13. So, feel free to use this range for the blue (negative) and red (positive) contrast.

3 data reorganizing

3.1 Basic reorganizing

  1. Remove unnecessary rows.
  2. Add âLeftâ and âRightâ side to the regions missing such indication
  3. Separate âoutcomeâ column
  4. Remove the first letter âzâ in MRI variable
Code
d_reorg <-
  d |> 
  # select(outcome, estimate, p, myqvallargervolumes) |> 
  select(outcome, estimate, p) |> 
  # Remove the two "mean" records
  dplyr::filter(! str_detect(outcome, "mean")) |>
  # Indicate the rows without "_Left" or "_Right" in the outcome column as "YES" for uniside variable
  mutate(uniside = if_else(str_detect(outcome, regex("Left$|Right$", ignore_case = TRUE)), "NO", "YES")) |> 
  # Create "rep" as replicating weight for the next step
  mutate(rep = if_else(uniside == "NO", 1, 2)) |> 
  # Use uncount() function to do the replication
  uncount(weights = rep, .id = "id", .remove = FALSE) |> 
  # Append "_Left" or "_Right" in the outcome records that originally have no Left or Right tagged
  mutate(
    outcome = case_when(
      rep == 2 & id == 1 ~ str_c(outcome, "_Left"),
      rep == 2 & id == 2 ~ str_c(outcome, "_Right"),
      TRUE ~ outcome
    )
  ) |> 
  separate(outcome, c("MRI", "region", "side")) |> 
  # All the "MRI" starts with letter "z". Remove it.
  mutate(MRI = str_remove(MRI, "^z"))

3.3 Remove duplicated columns

Widening the tibble lead to identical columns with names like uniside_FA_Left. Only keep one of them.

Code
d_dedup <-
  d_wide |>
  # Select all columns with "estimate" in the name,
  # and the first column with "uniside" in the name
  select(region,
         contains("estimate"),
         str_subset(colnames(d_wide), "uniside")[1]) |>
  # Rename the column with name like "uniside_FA_Left" to "uniside"
  rename_with( ~ str_replace(.x, "uniside_.*", "uniside")) |>
  # Replace the NA with "NO" in the uniside column
  mutate(uniside = if_else(is.na(uniside), "NO", uniside)) |>
  # Calculate the mean of the estimates
  rowwise() |>
  mutate(
    mean_FA = mean(c_across(contains("FA"))),
    mean_MD = mean(c_across(contains("MD"))),
    mean_ICVF = mean(c_across(contains("ICVF"))),
    mean_ISOVF = mean(c_across(contains("ISOVF"))),
    mean_OD = mean(c_across(contains("OD"))),
    mean_all = mean(c_across(contains("estimate")))
  )

3.4 Function to covert tibble to matrix

Code
make_matrix <- function(df, matrix_col, rowname_col = NULL) {
  my_matrix <- df %>%
    select({{ matrix_col }}) %>%
    as.matrix()

  if (!is.null(rownames)) {
    rownames(my_matrix) <- pull(df, {{ rowname_col }})
  }

  my_matrix
}

  d_dedup |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  summarise(across(contains("estimate"), ~ mean(.x, na.rm=TRUE))) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = everything()) |> 
  deframe()

row_ha <-
  rowAnnotation(Uniside = d_dedup$uniside,
                col = list(Uniside = set_names(
                  hue_pal(h.start = 60)(2), unique(d_dedup$uniside)
                )))

column_ha = HeatmapAnnotation(
  # mean = anno_barplot(MRI_mean, border = FALSE),
  MRI = MRI,
  side = side,
  col = list(
    MRI = set_names(brewer.pal(length(unique(MRI)), "Paired"), unique(MRI)),
    # side = set_names(hue_pal(h.start = 60)(2), unique(side))
    side = set_names(viridis(n = 2, option = "D"), unique(side))
  )
)

4.2 Heatmap

Uniside

Uniside denotes the MRI regions have no left/right sides. The same values were replicated and asigned to left/right sides to make the heatmap.

4.2.1 Order by mean values

Code
d_dedup |>
  make_matrix(matrix_col = contains("estimate"), rowname_col = region) %>%
  Heatmap(
   name = "Estimate",
   cluster_columns = FALSE,
   cluster_rows = FALSE,
   show_row_names = TRUE,
   
   # Title
   row_title = "Brain region",
   row_title_side = "left",
   row_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 16, fontface = "bold"),
   column_title = "Regression coefficient estimate",
   column_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 20, fontface = "bold"),
   
   # Names
   row_names_side = "left",
   # column_names_rot = 60,
   # column_names_centered = TRUE,
   show_column_names = FALSE,
   
   # Annotation
   right_annotation = row_ha,
   top_annotation = column_ha
  )

```{r}
  select(contains("estimate")) |> 
  # colnames(x=_) #|> 
  colnames() |> 
  str_extract("FA|MD|ISOVF|ICVF|OD")

# Means by MRI and side
MRI_mean <-
  d_dedup |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  summarise(across(contains("estimate"), ~ mean(.x, na.rm=TRUE))) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = everything()) |> 
  deframe()

row_ha <-
  rowAnnotation(Uniside = d_dedup$uniside,
                col = list(Uniside = set_names(
                  hue_pal(h.start = 60)(2), unique(d_dedup$uniside)
                )))

column_ha = HeatmapAnnotation(
  # mean = anno_barplot(MRI_mean, border = FALSE),
  MRI = MRI,
  side = side,
  col = list(
    MRI = set_names(brewer.pal(length(unique(MRI)), "Paired"), unique(MRI)),
    # side = set_names(hue_pal(h.start = 60)(2), unique(side))
    side = set_names(viridis(n = 2, option = "D"), unique(side))
  )
)

```

### Heatmap

::: {.callout-note collapse="false"}

## Uniside

Uniside denotes the MRI regions have no left/right sides.  The same values were replicated and asigned to left/right sides to make the heatmap.

:::

#### Order by mean values

```{r}
#| fig-height: 10
#| fig-width: 10

d_dedup |>
  make_matrix(matrix_col = contains("estimate"), rowname_col = region) %>%
  Heatmap(
   name = "Estimate",
   cluster_columns = FALSE,
   cluster_rows = FALSE,
   show_row_names = TRUE,
   
   # Title
   row_title = "Brain region",
   row_title_side = "left",
   row_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 16, fontface = "bold"),
   column_title = "Regression coefficient estimate",
   column_title_gp = gpar(fontsize = 20, fontface = "bold"),
   
   # Names
   row_names_side = "left",
   # column_names_rot = 60,
   # column_names_centered = TRUE,
   show_column_names = FALSE,
   
   # Annotation
   right_annotation = row_ha,
   top_annotation = column_ha
  )
```
